The paper deals with algorithmic approaches to connectivity problems on graphs, which are typically studied in computer science subfields such as data structures (cs.DS), computational geometry (cs.CG), graph theory (cs.GT), computational complexity (cs.CC), and theoretical computer science (cs.LG). The paper's focus on designing approximation algorithms for edge connectivity problems suggests that it is most likely to belong to the cs.DS and cs.CG subcategories, which often deal with optimization problems on graphs. The paper's use of graph decompositions and cycle covers also suggests that it may be relevant to the cs.GT subcategory, which studies the structure and properties of graphs. Finally, the paper's theoretical analysis of approximation guarantees and its use of linear programming techniques suggest that it may also be relevant to the cs.CC and cs.LG subcategories, which deal with the complexity and theoretical foundations of algorithms.
